hook.real_world_problem:
Your product catalog has 10,000 products. Every page load hits `productRepo.findAll()`. At 500 requests/second:

```
Without cache:  500 DB queries/second → database overloaded → slow responses
With @Cacheable: 1 DB query (first call), then 0 DB queries until cache expires
```

**Without caching:**
```java
@Service class ProductService {
    public List<Product> findAll() {
        return repo.findAll();  // hits DB every single call
    }
}
// 500 req/s = 500 DB queries/s = database bottleneck
```

**With one annotation:**
```java
@Service class ProductService {
    @Cacheable("products")  // ← that's it
    public List<Product> findAll() {
        return repo.findAll();  // hits DB ONCE, then returns cached copy
    }

    @CacheEvict("products")  // clear cache when products change
    public Product save(Product p) { return repo.save(p); }
}
// 500 req/s = 1 DB query (first) + 499 cache hits = ✅
```

The application context stays the same, the code change is one annotation, the performance gain is enormous. This is why caching is one of the most common interview topics for senior engineers.

concept_explanation.cacheable:
**@Cacheable — cache the return value:**

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {
    private final ProductRepository repo;

    // Cache entire list under key 'products::SimpleKey []':
    @Cacheable("products")
    public List<Product> findAll() {
        System.out.println("DB hit: findAll()");  // prints ONCE, then cached
        return repo.findAll();
    }

    // Cache by id: key = 'products::P001' etc.
    @Cacheable(value = "products", key = "#id")
    public Optional<Product> findById(String id) {
        System.out.println("DB hit: findById(" + id + ")");
        return repo.findById(id);
    }

    // Cache by category: key = 'products::Electronics'
    @Cacheable(value = "products", key = "#category")
    public List<Product> findByCategory(String category) {
        return repo.findByCategory(category);
    }

    // Conditional: only cache if list has items
    @Cacheable(value = "products", condition = "#result != null && !#result.isEmpty()")
    public List<Product> search(String query) {
        return repo.findByNameContaining(query);
    }

    // Unless: don't cache if empty result
    @Cacheable(value = "products", unless = "#result == null || #result.isEmpty()")
    public List<Product> hotProducts() {
        return repo.findHot();
    }
}
```

**How @Cacheable works:**
1. First call: cache miss → execute method → store return value in cache
2. Subsequent calls with same key: cache hit → return cached value, method NOT called

concept_explanation.cache_evict_put:
**@CacheEvict and @CachePut — keeping the cache consistent:**

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    // @CacheEvict: remove entry when data changes
    @CacheEvict(value = "products", key = "#product.id")
    public Product update(Product product) {
        return repo.save(product);  // evicts 'products::P001' from cache
    }

    // Evict ALL entries in the cache:
    @CacheEvict(value = "products", allEntries = true)
    public void reloadAll() {
        // Called by admin or after bulk import
    }

    // @CachePut: update the cache with new value (always executes the method)
    @CachePut(value = "products", key = "#result.id")
    public Product save(Product product) {
        return repo.save(product);  // saves AND puts result in cache
    }

    // @Caching: multiple cache operations on one method:
    @Caching(evict = {
        @CacheEvict(value = "products", key = "#id"),
        @CacheEvict(value = "products", allEntries = true)  // also clear list cache
    })
    public void delete(String id) {
        repo.deleteById(id);
    }
}
```

**Key difference:**
- `@CacheEvict`: remove from cache (next call will re-fetch from DB)
- `@CachePut`: update cache with method's return value (method always runs)

concept_explanation.caffeine_config:
**Caffeine cache — production-grade with TTL:**

```java
import com.github.benmanes.caffeine.cache.Caffeine;
import org.springframework.cache.caffeine.CaffeineCacheManager;

@Configuration
public class CacheConfig {

    @Bean
    public CacheManager cacheManager() {
        CaffeineCacheManager manager = new CaffeineCacheManager();
        manager.setCaffeine(Caffeine.newBuilder()
            .maximumSize(1000)            // max 1000 entries
            .expireAfterWrite(Duration.ofMinutes(10))  // TTL: 10 min after write
            .recordStats());              // enable hit/miss stats
        return manager;
    }
}

// OR via application.properties (simpler):
// spring.cache.type=caffeine
// spring.cache.caffeine.spec=maximumSize=1000,expireAfterWrite=10m
```

**Per-cache TTL configuration:**
```java
@Bean
public CacheManager cacheManager() {
    CaffeineCacheManager manager = new CaffeineCacheManager();
    // Different TTLs per cache:
    manager.registerCustomCache("products",
        Caffeine.newBuilder().maximumSize(500).expireAfterWrite(Duration.ofMinutes(5)).build());
    manager.registerCustomCache("prices",
        Caffeine.newBuilder().maximumSize(200).expireAfterWrite(Duration.ofSeconds(30)).build());
    manager.registerCustomCache("users",
        Caffeine.newBuilder().maximumSize(1000).expireAfterWrite(Duration.ofHours(1)).build());
    return manager;
}
```

concept_explanation.testing_cache:
**Testing cache behaviour with Spy:**

```java
@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = SpringBootTest.WebEnvironment.NONE)
class ProductServiceCacheTest {

    @Autowired ProductService productService;
    @Autowired CacheManager cacheManager;

    @BeforeEach
    void clearCache() {
        // Clear all caches between tests:
        cacheManager.getCacheNames().forEach(name ->
            cacheManager.getCache(name).clear());
    }

    @Test
    void findAll_calledTwice_dbHitOnceOnly() {
        // First call — DB hit:
        List<Product> result1 = productService.findAll();
        // Second call — cache hit (DB NOT called again):
        List<Product> result2 = productService.findAll();

        assertNotNull(result1);
        assertEquals(result1, result2);  // same list

        // Verify cache entry exists:
        Cache cache = cacheManager.getCache("products");
        assertNotNull(cache.get(SimpleKey.EMPTY));  // key for no-arg method
    }

    @Test
    void save_evictsCache() {
        productService.findAll();  // populate cache
        productService.save(new Product("New Mouse", 999));  // should evict

        // Verify cache was cleared:
        Cache cache = cacheManager.getCache("products");
        assertNull(cache.get(SimpleKey.EMPTY));  // cache entry gone
    }
}
```

